        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Here's your interactive full-stack TypeScript learning roadmap! Here's how it works:\n\n**Click any phase card** to expand it and see the detailed skill checklist. **Click the small checkboxes** to mark skills as you learn them — your progress is tracked on the bar at the top.\n\n## The 7 phases at a glance\n\n| Phase | Focus | Time |\n|-------|-------|------|\n| 1 | **TypeScript core** — types, generics, utility types, tsconfig | 3–4 weeks |\n| 2 | **Frontend with React + TS** — typed components, hooks, validation | 4–5 weeks |\n| 3 | **Backend with Node + TS** — Hono/Express, typed routes, middleware | 4–5 weeks |\n| 4 | **Database & ORM layer** — Prisma/Drizzle, migrations, typed queries | 3–4 weeks |\n| 5 | **Full-stack integration** — Next.js, tRPC, auth, monorepo | 4–6 weeks |\n| 6 | **Testing & quality** — Vitest, Playwright, MSW, linting | 2–3 weeks |\n| 7 | **Deploy & monitor** — Docker, CI/CD, Vercel/Fly.io, Sentry | 2–3 weeks |\n\n## A few tips for the journey\n\n- **Don't skip phase 1** — every later phase assumes you're comfortable with generics, discriminated unions, and narrowing. Rush this and the rest feels like guesswork.\n- **Phases 2 and 3 can overlap** — alternate frontend and backend days to stay fresh and start seeing the full picture sooner.\n- **Phase 5 is the payoff** — this is where the type-safety investment really compounds. When tRPC or server actions give you auto-complete from your database schema all the way to your UI, it clicks.\n- **Testing (phase 6) is portable** — Vitest + Testing Library patterns transfer to any TS project, so this is high-ROI time even if you switch frameworks later.\n\nTotal estimated time: **22–30 weeks** at a steady pace. Click into each phase in the widget above to track your progress!",
          "state": "done"
        }
      ]
    }
